03845nam a22007215i 9781400826063DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2009    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008260637 a10.1515/97814008260632doi  a(DE-B1597)528146  a(OCoLC)824153674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBC177 .F69 2006 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a177.71 aFrankfurt, Harry G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Reasons of Love /cHarry G. Frankfurt. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (112 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tOne. The Question: "How Should We Live?" -- tTwo. On Love, and Its Reasons -- tThree. The Dear Self -- tAcknowledgment0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis beautifully written book by one of the world's leading moral philosophers argues that the key to a fulfilled life is to pursue wholeheartedly what one cares about, that love is the most authoritative form of caring, and that the purest form of love is, in a complicated way, self-love. Harry Frankfurt writes that it is through caring that we infuse the world with meaning. Caring provides us with stable ambitions and concerns; it shapes the framework of aims and interests within which we lead our lives. The most basic and essential question for a person to raise about the conduct of his or her life is not what he or she should care about but what, in fact, he or she cannot help caring about. The most important form of caring, Frankfurt writes, is love, a nonvoluntary, disinterested concern for the flourishing of what is loved. Love is so important because meaningful practical reasoning must be grounded in ends that we do not seek only to attain other ends, and because it is in loving that we become bound to final ends desired for their own sakes. Frankfurt argues that the purest form of love is self-love. This sounds perverse, but self-love--as distinct from self-indulgence--is at heart a disinterested concern for whatever it is that the person loves. The most elementary form of self-love is nothing more than the desire of a person to love. Insofar as this is true, self-love is simply a commitment to finding meaning in our lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aLove. 0aPhilosophy. 0aPractical reason. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400826063zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400826063.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN